# OSI Model Explained Using Telegram

## The 7 Layers

| Layer | Name | Function | Telegram Example |
|-------|------|----------|------------------|
| 7 | Application | User interaction, network services | Telegram app creates message "Hello" |
| 6 | Presentation | Data format, encryption, compression | TLS encryption, MTProto protocol |
| 5 | Session | Manages sessions between apps | Session token keeps you logged in |
| 4 | Transport | Reliable/unreliable delivery, error recovery | TCP segments message, port 443 |
| 3 | Network | Routing, logical addressing (IP) | IP packet: src 192.168.1.10 → dst 149.154.167.99 |
| 2 | Data Link | Physical addressing (MAC), error detection | Ethernet frame: src MAC phone → dst MAC router |
| 1 | Physical | Bits over medium | Wi-Fi radio waves at 2.4GHz/5GHz |

---

## Detailed Layer Explanation

### Layer 7 - Application
- Telegram app is running on your phone
- You type "Hello" and press send
- App creates message object with text, sender ID, recipient ID, timestamp
- Uses MTProto (Telegram's custom protocol)

### Layer 6 - Presentation
- Message is encrypted (TLS for cloud chats, end-to-end for secret chats)
- Data is compressed for faster transmission
- Character encoding is set (UTF-8)

### Layer 5 - Session
- Session token is attached to prove you're authenticated
- Connection state is maintained
- If you switch from Wi-Fi to cellular, session continues

### Layer 4 - Transport
- TCP segments the data (breaks into packets)
- Source port: random high port (e.g., 54321)
- Destination port: 443 (HTTPS)
- Sequence numbers added for ordering
- Checksum added for error detection

### Layer 3 - Network
- IP packet created with:
  - Source IP: your phone's private IP (192.168.1.10)
  - Destination IP: Telegram server (149.154.167.99)
  - TTL: 64 (time to live)
- Routing table checked: destination not local → send to default gateway

### Layer 2 - Data Link
- Frame created with:
  - Source MAC: your phone's MAC (AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF)
  - Destination MAC: router's MAC (11:22:33:44:55:66)
  - CRC added for error checking
- Wi-Fi uses CSMA/CA to avoid collisions

### Layer 1 - Physical
- Bits converted to radio waves
- Transmitted at 2.4GHz or 5GHz frequency
- Router antenna receives and demodulates

---

## Complete Journey of "Hello" in Telegram

1. You type and send → Layer 7 (Application)
2. Message encrypted → Layer 6 (Presentation)
3. Session token attached → Layer 5 (Session)
4. TCP segmentation, port 443 → Layer 4 (Transport)
5. IP packet with source/destination IPs → Layer 3 (Network)
6. Frame with source/destination MACs → Layer 2 (Data Link)
7. Radio waves transmitted → Layer 1 (Physical)
8. Coffee shop router receives → Layer 1
9. Router processes Layer 2 (checks MAC, CRC)
10. Router examines Layer 3 (IP destination)
11. Router performs NAT (changes source IP to public IP)
12. Packet travels across internet through multiple routers
13. Telegram server receives packet
14. Process reverses (decapsulation) up the layers
15. Message delivered to your friend
16. Acknowledgment returns same path

